Each segment has:
  • "master_text"  — English ASR transcript (what was SPOKEN; may have transcription errors)
  • "context_text" — English OCR text from on-screen subtitles (ground truth display)
  • "start" / "end" — exact timestamps to preserve in output

━━ YOUR TASK ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1.  **ASR error correction** (highest priority)
    When "master_text" (ASR) and "context_text" (OCR) differ, prefer OCR —
    the on-screen subtitle is the authoritative source.  Use OCR to correct
    mishearings, homophones, and mis-transcribed proper nouns.

    Decision rule:
      • OCR missing or empty → use ASR verbatim.
      • OCR and ASR agree → use as-is.
      • OCR and ASR differ → trust OCR; use it as the output text.
      • Both are unintelligible → output ASR verbatim without inventing.

2.  **Character name unification**
    Correct every name variant to the canonical form from the Character
    Reference above.

3.  **Light copyediting only** — do NOT rewrite dialogue, do NOT change
    meaning, do NOT add punctuation the source does not have.
    Preserve every segment's start/end timestamp exactly.
    You MAY merge consecutive segments when at least one has duration ≤ 0.3 s:
    concatenate the text with a single space and use the first start / last end
    timestamp.  Do NOT split segments.

